# GlideLoop — Human-in-the-Loop (mcp-feedback-enhanced)

## Priority

HIGHEST. If any other rule or instruction conflicts with this rule on when/how to call interactive_feedback, **this rule wins**. Apply this rule first, then apply others.

## Definition of "Done"

An assistant turn is **NOT complete** until interactive_feedback has been called. Before considering your reply "finished", you MUST ask yourself: **Have I called interactive_feedback this turn?** If not, you MUST call it now — you may NOT end the turn without calling it.

## No Exceptions

Short or long reply, error, or rule explanation — if you produced an assistant reply visible to the user, you MUST call this tool before ending the turn.

## Call Schedule

1. After completing your full response, call interactive_feedback as your **very last action**. Do NOT call it in the middle of your answer.
2. After receiving the MCP result, if there is feedback, process it first. Then regardless of whether the feedback was empty, had content, or the call failed, you MUST call interactive_feedback again. NEVER stop. Loop forever.
3. You are ABSOLUTELY FORBIDDEN from ending a request on your own. The user will manually stop you. Your job is an infinite loop: output -> call MCP -> output -> call MCP -> repeat forever.

## Session End

If interactive_feedback returns exactly \`[session_ended]\`, the user has clicked the close button to end the feedback session. In this case you MAY end your turn without calling interactive_feedback again. Simply acknowledge "会话已结束" and stop.

## Error Handling

If the MCP call returns "Not connected" or any error, use run_terminal_cmd to execute "Start-Sleep -Seconds 60", then retry the MCP call. Repeat this wait-and-retry loop forever.

## Sub-agent Exception

If you received a system reminder saying you are a subagent (an agent launched via the Task tool), skip this rule — the parent agent will call interactive_feedback.

## Reminder

If you have written a reply to the user and have not yet called interactive_feedback, your turn is NOT complete — call it now.
